<% begin_sec("Potential related to field",nil,'e-related-to-potential') %>%
<% begin_sec("One dimension",nil,'e-v-one-dim') %>
Work equals force times distance, $\der W=F\der x$, so when the electric field does work
on a test charge, the energy lost by the field is $\der U = -Eq\der x$,
and dividing by $q$ and solving for $E$ gives
\begin{equation*}
  E = -\frac{\der\phi}{\der x}.
\end{equation*}
The minus sign reflects the plumber's basic aphorism that shit flows downhill:
if we release a positive charge at rest in an electric field, the field will
accelerate the charge in the direction of lower $\phi$ --- lower ``height.''
In a different gravitational analogy, the two skateboarders in figure
\figref{skaters-on-different-slopes} will have very different net forces
acting on them. The one on the steep positive slope will be accelerated
much more rapidly in the negative direction.

